On Thu, Apr 5, 2012 at 3:26 PM, Markus Lanthaler
&lt;markus.lanthaler@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; Is something like hal+json Linked Data?
&gt;
&gt; That&#39;s a difficult question to answer but I would tend to say no as you
&gt; treat the data as an opaque block. The properties in there have no meaning
&gt; and there&#39;s no way to, e.g., describe that two properties in two different
&gt; representations are about the same thing.
&gt;

The approach with HAL is that the meaning of a resource and its
properties are given to it by the link relation which led to its
discovery. So if you follow a link relation &#39;user&#39; and you get back a
representation of a resource that includes the property &#39;age&#39; - you
know the meaning of that property is &#39;the age of this user (resource)&#39;
because the user rel has documentation which tells you that.

Personally, I think that approach is sufficient - buf if you
desperately felt the need to have your HAL representations explicitly
typed so that they can &#39;stand on their own&#39; and not require a
preceding link relation, then you could use a profile link to do this
job (a la dret&#39;s ongoing work). I think that&#39;s a poor design decision,
but it is perfectly possible.


&gt;&gt; Do you agree that hal+json is simpler than JSON-LD?
&gt;
&gt; Not really, but that depends on what you mean by simpler. If you are just
&gt; talking about extracting hyperlinks then, yeah, maybe, because you just have
&gt; to look for &quot;_links&quot; whereas in JSON-LD potentially every value could be an
&gt; IRI (by setting the type of that property to @id). But in the end that&#39;s
&gt; just a &quot;trick&quot; since you split every link in a &quot;rel&quot; and &quot;href&quot; part whereas
&gt; in JSON-LD the &quot;rel&quot; is the property itself and its value is the &quot;href&quot;.
&gt;

That isn&#39;t a &quot;trick&quot;, it&#39;s just a good way of emulating Atom/HTML&#39;s
&lt;link&gt; and @rel with JSON.

&gt;&gt; Is there anything about hal+json that you consider insufficient or
&gt;&gt; &#39;wrong&#39; as a means to expose a REST application to machines?
&gt;
&gt; There&#39;s nothing wrong with it but I think it&#39;s expressivity is quite
&gt; limited.

What would you like to do that you couldn&#39;t with HAL?

Cheers,
Mike
